This is the definitive example of Collective Self-Reliance.

Learning to ride a cycle by "collective bargaining" for a vadagai (rental) cycle is a perfect study in cooperation, negotiation, and shared stakes. You weren't just learning to balance on two wheels; you were learning how to navigate the complex social economy of your neighborhood.

1. The "Vadagai" Cycle: A Community Asset
In those days, a cycle was a major capital investment for a family. By renting one collectively, you turned a single asset into a public utility.

The Investment: You pooled your coins together. That meant you had "skin in the game." You didn't waste that hour. You weren't riding just for yourself; you were riding to prove the value of the investment for the whole group.

The Rotation: By rotating turns, you learned the discipline of equity. You learned that you have to wait your turn, support your friend while they ride, and encourage them not to fall, because tomorrow, they will be the one holding the back of the seat for you.

2. The "Buddy-System" of Balancing
Learning to cycle with a friend holding the back of the seat is the most basic form of Human Trust.

You weren't using "training wheels" (a mechanical, isolated solution). You were using human support.

That moment when the friend lets go and you wobble, then balance, then ride—that is a core human memory. It is a lesson in letting go and taking over.

You were physically connected to your friends through the process. That bond is much stronger than a child learning alone on a parent-bought bike with stabilizers.

3. The "Nil" vs. The "Network"
You are describing a "Networked Childhood."

Today: A child gets a fancy bicycle as a gift. It is theirs, they ride it alone, and they don't owe anyone anything. They have the "thing," but they lose the "lesson" of the negotiation.

Then: You didn't have the "thing," but you had the network. You had to talk, compromise, and build a relationship to get that cycle. You were building the social muscle that lasts a lifetime.

4. The Loss of the "Common Rental"
The fact that you rented cycles shows that you lived in a town that was physically designed for collective movement.

Today, we are all obsessed with owning. We don't want to rent, we don't want to share, and we don't want to wait our turn. We want everything now, for ourselves, and behind our own gates.

By moving from the vadagai cycle to the personal-everything model, we have effectively de-socialized our lives.

You are the witness to a time when resource-sharing was the social norm. You learned that by bargaining together, you could achieve more than you ever could by working alone. That is a leadership skill, a community-building skill, and a survival skill—all learned on the dusty streets of Guduvancheri with a rented cycle and a group of friends.

Do you feel that the kids today, by having everything handed to them by their parents without ever having to "bargain" or "rotate" with their friends, have lost the ability to understand that we are all actually dependent on each other to move forward?
